The values formula_16 are usually chosen to obtain a specified significance level formula_17, through the relation formula_18. The Neyman-Pearson lemma states that this likelihood ratio test is the most powerful among all level formula_17 tests for this problem.
Definition (likelihood ratio test for composite hypotheses).
A null hypothesis is often stated by saying the parameter formula_3 is in a specified subset formula_21 of the parameter space formula_22.
The likelihood function is formula_24 (with formula_2 being the pdf or pmf), which is a function of the parameter formula_3 with formula_27 held fixed at the value that was actually observed, "i.e.", the data. The likelihood ratio test statistic is 
Here, the formula_9 notation refers to the supremum function.
A likelihood ratio test is any test with critical region (or rejection region) of the form formula_30 where formula_31 is any number satisfying formula_32. Many common test statistics such as the "Z"-test, the "F"-test, Pearson's chi-squared test and the "G"-test are tests for nested models and can be phrased as log-likelihood ratios or approximations thereof.
Interpretation.
Being a function of the data formula_27, the likelihood ratio is therefore a statistic. The likelihood ratio test rejects the null hypothesis if the value of this statistic is too small. How small is too small depends on the significance level of the test, "i.e.", on what probability of Type I error is considered tolerable ("Type I" errors consist of the rejection of a null hypothesis that is true).
The numerator corresponds to the maximum likelihood of an observed outcome under the null hypothesis. The denominator corresponds to the maximum likelihood of an observed outcome varying parameters over the whole parameter space. The numerator of this ratio is less than the denominator. The likelihood ratio hence is between 0 and 1. Low values of the likelihood ratio mean that the observed result was less likely to occur under the null hypothesis as compared to the alternative. High values of the statistic mean that the observed outcome was nearly as likely to occur under the null hypothesis as compared to the alternative, and the null hypothesis cannot be rejected.
Distribution: Wilks's theorem.
If the distribution of the likelihood ratio corresponding to a particular null and alternative hypothesis can be explicitly determined then it can directly be used to form decision regions (to accept/reject the null hypothesis). In most cases, however, the exact distribution of the likelihood ratio corresponding to specific hypotheses is very difficult to determine. A convenient result, attributed to Samuel S. Wilks, says that as the sample size formula_34 approaches formula_35, the test statistic formula_36 for a nested model will be asymptotically formula_37-distributed with degrees of freedom equal to the difference in dimensionality of formula_22 and formula_21. This means that for a great variety of hypotheses, a practitioner can compute the likelihood ratio formula_5 for the data and compare formula_41 to the formula_37 value corresponding to a desired statistical significance as an approximate statistical test.
Examples.
Coin tossing.
